# Solution
############################################################

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
We use [`r`] to represent radius and [`d`] to represent diameter. In this problem, it's given that the diameter is [`[$diameterMO]\text{.}`] A circle's radius is half as long as its diameter, so the radius is [`[$radiusMO]\text{.}`]

Throughout these computations, all quantities have units attached, but we only show them in the final step.
a.  [`\newcommand{\amp}{&}\begin{aligned}[t]
                    c\amp = \pi d\\
                    \amp = \pi \cdot [$diameter]\\
                    \amp = [$circumferenceWithPiMO]
                    \end{aligned}
                    `]

a.  [`\newcommand{\amp}{&}\begin{aligned}[t]
                    c\amp = \pi d\\
                    \amp \approx 3.1415926 \cdot [$diameter]\\
                    \amp \approx [$circumferenceMO]
                    \end{aligned}
                    `]

a.  [`\newcommand{\amp}{&}\begin{aligned}[t]
                    A\amp = \pi r^2\\
                    \amp = \pi \cdot [$radius]^2\\
                    \amp = \pi \cdot [$radiusSquared]\\
                    \amp = [$areaWithPiMO]
                    \end{aligned}
                    `]

a.  [`\newcommand{\amp}{&}\begin{aligned}[t]
                    A\amp = \pi r^2\\
                    \amp \approx 3.1415926 \cdot [$radius]^2\\
                    \amp \approx 3.1415926 \cdot [$radiusSquared]\\
                    \amp \approx [$areaMO]
                    \end{aligned}
                    `]

END_PGML_SOLUTION

